The Tobar an Dualchais/Kist o Riches website contains material from three sound collections: the School of Scottish Studies Sound Archive; the National Trust for Scotland's Canna Sound Archive Collection; and BBC Radio nan Gàidheal .  The website encompasses many aspects of the culture and heritage of Scotland and its diaspora . Material available includes folklore, songs, music, history, poetry, traditions, stories, poetry and information on traditional occupations and ways of life . The material on the Tobar an Dualchais/Kist o Riches website comes from three sound collections: the School of Scottish Studies Sound Archive; BBC Radio nan Gàidheal; and National Trust for Scotland's Canna Sound Archive Collection .  Tobar an Dualchais/Kist o Riches is a collaborative project which was set up to preserve, digitise, catalogue and make several thousand hours of Gaelic and Scots oral recordings available online . Material available includes folklore, songs, music, history, poetry, traditions, stories, poetry and information on traditional occupations and ways of life, including those of Scottish Travellers .  The oral tradition and intergenerational passing on of songs and stories are in decline in our ever-increasing digital world . However, our collections presents new opportunities to engage larger audiences with traditional arts through digital mediums for future generations .  An ongoing project recording the memories of people who have lived and worked in Dundee and the surrounding area . Musicians, jute workers, academics, designers and poets are just a few of those whose experiences have been captured so far .  The University of Aberdeen Oral History Archive began in 1985 as part of the Aberdeen University Quincentenary Project . The archive contains nearly 200 interviews with over 170 individuals connected with the University . The recordings date from the 1970s to the current day .  A collection of oral history recordings held in the local history and archive collections of West Dunbartonshire Council . The recordings date from the 1970s to the current day . The Wick Voices collection aims to preserve as many stories as possible for posterity . Written reminiscences and oral histories relating to the Clydebank Blitz, the Singer Factory, shipbuilding and other industries are also held .  Wick Voices is the Oral History Section of The Wick Society . The ambitious project, set up in 2016 and run by a small team of volunteers, seeks to preserve as many memories as possible, through digital recording and archiving technology . The extensive collection is available online .  Wick Voices is a truly intergenerational project working closely with school pupils and older family members . The Wick Society is at the hub of the project, helping to promote interest in our shared heritage . The extensive collection is available online .

Description: Why you should rip CDs to lossless audio formats . The most important choice is the format of the resulting digital music file . Collection includes Yiddish songs, klezmer music and vaudeville acts from the United States, the former Soviet Union and Israel .  Robert Freedman and Molly Freedman have been collecting Yiddish music for 63 years . The Freedmans started collecting the records and songs in their Philadelphia apartment . Title: Artists open up John Peel's historic vinyl collection - BBC News
Description: John Peel's massive archive of vinyl comprises decades of UK music sent directly to him at the point of release . Album sleeves bulge with personal notes from Bowie, Marc Bolan, even long-time friend John Lennon sending a copy of Two Virgins with a hand-written explanation of the stereo mix .  John Peel filled in tens of thousands of filing cards representing each album . Each record also has Peel's "star system" of preferred plays, with three stars signifying it was probably played on air .  Tom Ravenscroft has 120,000 records in his Peel Acres collection . Rare finds include a Jimi Hendrix bootleg This Flyer and a Sex Pistols test pressing of Anarchy .

Title: 8 ways to discover new music in 2022 | Bandwagon | Music media
Description: Listening to the same songs on a cyclical loop can start to get mundane after an extended period of time . Here are some surefire ways in which you can discover fresh new tunes to kickstart the year .  Spotify, Apple Music, and Tidal have (almost) every recorded album available in their database; unless you’re looking for obscure black metal demos or something of that nature . There are also archival sites that cater specifically to different genres of music—this includes 'The Metal Archives' and 'Classical Archives'  The Classical Archives pays homage to the greats of the genre such as Bach, Beethoven, Bernstein . The Hip-hop Archive and Research Institute champions hip-hop culture by supporting and recording anything related to the said genre of music . Podcasts are a valuable resource for learning about new releases as music commentary is seemingly inexhaustible .

Title: Not Brahms and Liszt on WMBR Cambridge
Description: Not Brahms and Liszt is a weekly radio program on MIT's student and community radio station, WMBR . It features classical music of the 20th and 21st centuries, from Reich to Nyman to Wolfe to Higdon and onward .  The show of music for guitar began with Aaron Larget-Caplan's recording of his own honey cadence . The show concluded with trumpeter Natsuki Tamura's .  The Great Necks Guitar Trio recorded Nestor's arrangement of Maurice Ravel's 1932-1933 Don Quichotte à Dulcinée . Frederic Hand's recording of his own A Waltz for Maurice . The show concluded with an excerpt from Joseph Summer's 2006 Opera Hamlet .  The show began with Roomful Of Teeth's recording of the fourth movement (The Acoustic Constellation, Spring) of Michael Harrison's (Cantaloupe Music) 2015-2016 Just Constellations for vocal octet . The show of electronic music by female composers began with Johanna Beyer's 1938 Music of the Spheres . It continued with Annea Lockwood's 2013 Buoyant and her 2012 Dusk .  Rzewski's 1992 De Profundis for piano and spoken voice is excerpted from a letter written by Oscar Wilde near the end of his two year imprisonment in Reading Gaol for homosexual acts . The show continued with Kronos Quartet's recording of Scott Johnson's 1991-3 Cold War Suite from How It Happens .  Skylark Vocal Ensemble's recording of Daniel Elder's 2013 composition Elegy was inspired by the Taps bugle call and whose text by Horace Lorenzo Trim was written to accompany Taps . The show continued with three songs written by Ruth Lomon (Wikipedia, Brandeis, Bruce Duffie) in 1996, off her 2002 reflection on the Holocaust .  This was a show of music at the boundary of composition and improvisation, and at the intersection of classical music and jazz . We celebrated the work of British composer and conductor Peter Maxwell Davies .  The show began with William Price's 2005 composition Hook, Line and Sinker, recorded by Christopher Ayer on clarinet, Brian Utley on saxophone and Kae Hosoda-Ayer on piano . Next came three pieces by pianist Anthony de Mare from his Liaisons Project, in which 36 contemporary composers were invited to choose a song by Stephen Sondheim and re-imagine it as a solo piano piece . Oskar Sala recorded Paul Hindemith's 1930 composition 7 Pieces for 3 Trautoniums .  The ZOFO (ZO = 20, FO = Finger Orchestra) four-hand piano duet's 2015 recording of Riley's 1985 composition Half-Wolf Dances Mad in Moonlight . The show concluded with Chris Fisher-Lochhead's 2015 composition Hack, commissioned by Spektral Quartet, for whom it was commisioned .  We celebrated the work of composer Pierre Boulez, who died last week at the age of 90 . The show began with Elliott Carter's 1965 Piano Concerto, performed by Ursula Oppens and the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Michael Gielen . We continued with María Huld Markan Sigfúsdóttir's 2010 composition Sleeping Pendulum .  Alan Beeler's 1986 composition Homage to Roger Sessions performed by Czech Radio Symphony Orchestra with Vladimír Válek conducting . The show concluded with Igor Stravinsky's 1913 composition The Rite of Spring .  The show used Steve Reich's 1971 composition Drumming as its bed music . The show started with clarinettist Catriana Scott's performance of Cheryl Frances-Hoad's 2008 composition Bouleumata (ability to deliberate) The show concluded with a performance of David Cheskey's 2015 composition Arbeit Macht Frei .  This was a show of new releases on the Bridge Records label . Bruce Duffie conducted excellent interviews of John Cage and Joan La Barbara . The show concluded with Don Plonsey's Stay Fresh Baggies 4, off the new release Killer Tuba Songs, Vol.   Nyman's chamber opera The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat is based on the Oliver Sacks neurological case study . Stockhausen's 1968 composition Stimmung is also based on a case study of Sacks case .

Title: Listen to the Eerie Warbles of the Oldest Sound Recording in History
Description: On April 9, 1860, French inventor Édouard-Léon Scott de Martinville created the first sound recording in history . With his phonautograph, Scott was trying to artificially reconstruct the anatomy of the human ear in order to produce visual images of sound waves for research and preservation . A group of scientists at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in California has translated these recordings into audio files .

Title: Why Hidizs Supports MQA Audio Technology？
Description: There are 4 mainstream audio file formats on the market: PCM, DSD, MQA, and AAC . The higher the format, the larger the file and the clearer it is, Hidizs says . The most common pure audio formats are lossless and lossy formats derived from PCM .  PCM waveform played back by PCM is quite close to the actual sound, which is highly suitable for music playback . DSD uses the difference in pulse signal density to fit the waveform, so the sampling times are much higher than PCM, and the amount of information continuously captured is also larger .  MQA has an impressive feature: multiple unfoldings . The technology packages music recordings [as 44. 1 or 48 kHz files] for efficient streaming and storage . The MqA decoder unfolds to the original resolution, or to the highest capability of the hardware . The Hidizs MS1 Rainbow, MS2, and a range of new Hi-Res in-ear monitors can clearly deliver the stereo-like and airy quality .

tweet: From sheet music to the ghostly notes on a worn 78 to the clarity of digital music, every note is a plea to be heard. https://t.co/9z4JafGrei
Title: The Women Behind the First Black Music Magazine - Atlas Obscura
Description: There are just two surviving issues of The Musical Messenger, which ran from 1886 to 1891 . Amelia Tilghman was a musician and educator from Washington, D.C. The magazine was the first of its kind, but it was hardly the first example of Black journalism in America .  The Musical Messenger was founded in 1856 by a prominent Black family in Washington, D. C. She was a well-known musician, writer and journalist . The magazine had two purposes: to provide the musical news of the day, and to advocate for equality .  Music historian Juanita Karpf speculated that the addition of the Bragg family name to the masthead of The Musical Messenger contributed to the paper's longevity . Other articles were pointedly and explicitly about politics and race, such as “Colored Loafers: To the Young Colored Men of America”  Tilghman heard her people, and wanted the nation to hear them, too . From sheet music to the ghostly notes on a worn 78 to the clarity of digital music, every note is a plea to be heard .

You may come across half a dozen different audio file formats without even realizing it. Knowing the specifics of each format will help you choose the best one for whichever project you’re working on.
https://t.co/9F0AmJKNZD
Title: WAV vs MP3: Which Audio File Format Should I Use?| CrumplePop
Description: The main difference between digital audio file types lies in whether the file is compressed or not . Compressed files store less data but also occupy less disk space . However, compressed files have lower audio quality and can feature compression artifacts . To achieve CD-quality audio, you should use uncompressed files at 44. 1kHz and 16-bit depth .  The rise to fame of MP3 and WAV formats defines the history of recorded music . MP3 files are a compressed audio format that minimizes the file size by sacrificing sound quality . WAV files undergo minimal processing from the original recording and contain all the information transformed from analog to digital when the original audio was recorded . The higher the volume, the more evident the differences in quality sound .  Peer-to-peer file-sharing services allow distributing and downloading of digital music . MP3 files were by far the most common format as they would decrease bandwidth use while providing good-quality music . Napster, the first P2P service to reach worldwide fame, had 80 million active users at its peak .  P2P networks made music available to anyone, anywhere, and allowed listeners to discover and share new music at ground-breaking speed compared to earlier times . The increasing internet bandwidth and power of personal computers gave people the chance to share more and more media files online . The process of freeing music from its physical constraints led to an ever-increasing audience interested in higher audio quality .  Musicians and audiophiles should always go for formats that undergo the least possible processing when converted from analog to digital, namely WAV and AIFF audio files . If you’re sharing high-quality music online, you should opt for a lossless format like FLAC .  This website uses cookies to improve your experience while you navigate through the website . We also use third-party cookies that help us analyze and understand how you use this website . These cookies will be stored in your browser only with your consent .

tweet: Exploring the Provenance of Italian Manuscript Editions in the Royal Music Library - Music blog https://t.co/OwWsUocmOY https://t.co/4yVIZeASkA
Title: Exploring the Provenance of Italian Manuscript Editions in the Royal Music Library - Music blog
Description: The Royal Music Library represents the music interests and collecting efforts of several British monarchs and members of the royal family . Establishing the line of provenance for the majority of individual volumes in the collection is a challenging task . Each volume contains the musical hands of a number of different copyists, based mainly in Venice or Naples, both major music publishing centres in the late 18th century .  Most of the music in this sub-collection was acquired in Italy, in the late 18th century, probably in Naples and Venice, and subsequently brought back to England . The names 'Cawdor' and 'Elizabeth Campbell' denote ownership of Italian manuscript editions .  Elizabeth’s name (either as Campbell or Cawdor) that appears on an individual edition, sometimes accompanied by ‘1817’, suggests either that she acquired in Italy in 1817 or, perhaps, that she was gifted it by her husband upon marriage . The vast majority of individual editions in this sub-collection belonged to John and Elizabeth, First Earl and Countess of Cawd . The second part of this blog, to be published in a few weeks’ time, will follow the journey of these vellum volumes from the family to Prince Albert

"Most popular music is conceived in what’s called 4/4 meter, also known as 4/4 time, as indicated in sheet music and Guitar World’s rhythmic tab notation by the visual symbol, or time signature, 4/4, appearing at the beginning of a piece of music." 

https://t.co/NJZP9xQDi7
Title: Beginner guitar: lock down your rhythm playing with this lesson in basic note durations | Guitar World
Description: Guitar World’s rhythmic tab notation is based on the basic principles of rhythm and rhythmic notation . The number 4 signifies that a quarter note receives one beat in each bar of music . The bottom number, or denominator, of the time signature indicates what kind of rhythmic value is serving as the foundational beat .  In rhythmic tab, a tab number or stack of tab numbers enclosed in a circle or oval, with a vertical stem below it, indicates a half-note . In a bar of 4/4 meter, you can have several possible combinations of quarter notes and/or half notes that add up to four beats . They must always equal 1, or one whole note, per the time signature of the bar .

Title: How to choose the best audio format for podcasts?
Description: Audio file format is how digital audio is stored on computers, mobile phones, and other devices . The most popular audio type that both professionals and non-professionals frequently deal with is MP3 . We’re about to explain to you the popular file types and help you choose the best audio format for your shows .  WAV is one of the most popular formats if you record audio on a professional level . AIFF is the second popular choice for recording, mastering, and mixing the audios after WAV . Common lossless audio formats are ALAC and FLAC .  MP3 is the best option to save your audio or upload it to iTunes, Spotify and other podcast directories . If you initially recorded your podcast in a format other than MP3, you can upload, edit, and save it as MP3 with Podcastle .

In its present- https://t.co/6MpWkeWqAh
Title: Tape recorder - Wikipedia
Description: The earliest known audio tape recorder was a non-magnetic, non-electric version invented by Alexander Graham Bell's Volta Laboratory and patented in 1886 (U.S. Patent 341,214) It employed a 3⁄16-inch-wide (4.8 mm) strip of wax-covered paper that was coated by dipping it in a solution of beeswax and paraffin and then had one side scraped clean, with the other side allowed to harden . In playback mode, a dull, loosely mounted stylus, attached to a rubber diaphrag  The waxed tape recording medium was inferior to Edison's wax cylinder recording medium . The celluloid film was inscribed and played back with a stylus, in a manner similar to the wax cylinders of Edison's gramophone .  Widespread use of wire recording occurred within the decades spanning from 1940 until 1960 . Wire was also used as a recording medium in black box voice recorders for aviation in the 1950s .  Magnetic tape recording as we know it today was developed in Germany during the 1930s at BASF (then part of the chemical giant IG Farben) and AEG in cooperation with the state radio RRG . Fritz Pfleumer's 1928 invention of paper tape with oxide powder lacquered onto it . The first practical tape recorder from AEG was the Magnetophon K1, demonstrated in Germany in 1935 .  Bing Crosby was the first major American music star to use tape to pre-record radio broadcasts, and the first to master commercial recordings on tape . Mullin's unit soon amassed a collection of hundreds of low-quality magnetic dictating machines .  Poniatoff, whose initials became part of the company name, soon became the world leader in the development of tape recording, with its Model 200 tape deck . The BBC acquired some Magnetophon machines in 1946 on an experimental basis, and these were used in the early stages of the new Third Programme to record and play back operas from Germany .  The 8-track tape standard, developed by Bill Lear in the mid-1960s, popularized consumer audio playback in automobiles . In 1990, the Compact Cassette was the dominant format in mass-market recorded music . The development of Dolby noise reduction technology in the 1960s also contributed to its popularity .  There are a wide variety of tape recorders in existence, from small hand-held devices to large multitrack machines . The storage of an analog signal on tape works well, but is not perfect . The granular nature of the magnetic material adds high-frequency noise to the signal .  Magnetic tape brought about sweeping changes in both radio and the recording industry . Sound could be recorded, erased and re-recorded on the same tape many times, sounds could be duplicated from tape to tape with only minor loss of quality . Tape made possible the first sound recordings totally created by electronic means, opening the way for the bold sonic experiments of the Musique Concrète school and avant-garde composers like Karlheinz Stockhausen .  The Allies were aware of the existence of the pre-war Magnetophon recorders, but not of the introduction of high-frequency bias and PVC-backed tape . Mullin claims to have been the first to use "canned laughter"; at the insistence of Bill Morrow, he inserted a segment of raucous laughter from an earlier show into a later show that hadn't worked well .  This article incorporates text from the United States National Museum Bulletin, a government publication in the public domain . It is a detailed, illustrated 17-page article is a fundamental source for early history of magnetic (wire/tape) recording: https://://://worldradiohistory.com/Archive-All-Audio/. - A History of Magnetic Recording BBC/H2G2- A Selected History of magnetic Recording .- Walter Weber's Technical Innovation at the Reichs-Rundfunk-Gesellschaft .- Timeline from U of San Diego's Archive at the Wayback Machine .

tweet: . research finds that an app mandated for all attendees of the Beijing2022 Olympics "has a simple but devastating flaw where encryption protecting users’ voice audio & file transfers can be trivially sidestepped." This makes space for hacking. https://t.co/WyvETo5lwW
Title: Cross-Country Exposure: Analysis of the MY2022 Olympics App - The Citizen Lab
Description: MY2022, an app mandated for use by all attendees of the 2022 Olympic Games in Beijing, has a flaw where encryption protecting users’ voice audio and file transfers can be trivially sidestepped . Server responses can also be spoofed, allowing an attacker to display fake instructions to users . The app collects a range of highly sensitive medical information, it is unclear with whom or which organization(s) it shares this information .  MY2022 is required to be installed by all attendees to the 2022 Winter Olympic Games in China . The app is multi-purpose, implementing a wide range of functionality including real-time chat, voice audio chat, file transfers, as well as news and weather updates about the Olympic Games . It can also be used to submit required health customs information for those visiting China from abroad, which includes submitting passport details, demographic information, travel and medical histories .  MY2022 is fairly straightforward about the types of information it collects and with which third-party entities it shares information . For domestic users, the app collects personal information including name, national ID number, phone number, email address, profile picture, and employment information . My2022’s privacy policy did not specify with whom or with which organization(s) it would share users’ medical and health-related information .  MY2022 fails to validate SSL certificates, allowing an attacker to spoof trusted servers by interfering with the communication between the app and these servers . This failure to validate means the app can be deceived into connecting to a malicious host while believing it is a trusted host . Some sensitive data is transmitted without any encryption or any security at all .  MY2022 app contains a list of 2,442 keywords generally considered politically sensitive in China . Most of the keywords are in simplified Chinese, with a small portion in Tibetan, Uyghur, traditional Chinese, and English . The list includes negative references to the Chinese political system and intra-party power struggles .  MY2022’s Uyghur and Tibetan script keywords are not directly related to recent controversies such as the “reeducation camps’.  Rather, the keywords relate to Uyughur issues or Islam commonly censored in China . My2022 does not utilize its built-in blocklist to censor users’ communications. The reporting feature is not novel or unusual for Chinese applications .  It is reasonable to ask whether the encryption in this app was intentionally sabotaged for surveillance purposes or whether the defect was born of developer negligence . However, the case for the Chinese government sabotaging MY2022’s encryption is problematic .  MY2022 is an app that processes a wide range of sensitive personal information including users’ passport information and health status . My2022’s insecure transmission of personal information may constitute a direct violation of China's privacy laws . Apps on Android phones may be governed by two different sets of Google policies .  Chinese apps ranging from banking apps to video streaming platforms have been found to excessively collect sensitive user data, often without user consent . MY2022’s functionality to report other users for “politically sensitive” expression is common in other Chinese apps, such as chat apps, live streaming apps, mobile games and even open source software .

Description: Library of Congress has new arrangements digitized and available for download . “Lift Every Voice and Sing (National Hymn for the Colored People of America)” is “respectfully dedicated to Booker T. Washington” The song was first published in 1900 . It wasn’t until 1919 that the NAACP adopted the song as an official rallying cry for civil rights . tweet: What Is Sheet Music? With 11 Top Examples & History https://t.co/maruzi1cNj https://t.co/BeWjKWY4aX
Title: What Is Sheet Music? With 11 Top Examples & History - Music Industry How To
Description: What Is Sheet Music?  With 11 Top Examples & History of the notation system . Good sheet music should tell you everything you need to know about how to play a piece . A score is a type of sheet music that outlines all parts of a piece of music .  A treble clef sits in the staff, and it curls around the second line, which gives that line the pitch of G . Middle C sits right in between the two, so you can play more of the piano or harp's range . The tenor clef isn't a primary clef for any instrument, but the bassoon, cello, and trombone all use it occasionally .  You can find the key signature after the clef at the beginning of a piece . The most common key signature is a 4/4, and that means each measure has four quarter notes . The time signature is one number on top of another that tells you what type of note gets a beat .  The notes tell you what pitch to play, when to play it, and how long you should play that pitch . Common note durations include the whole note, half note, quarter note, and eighth note . Some sheet music will have bars with two thin lines after, and that indicates the end of a section of the piece .  A slur is a curved line that connects one note to the next . A fermata indicates you should hold that note for longer than its value . A staccato looks like a dot below or above the note (opposite the direction of the note stem) A tenuto is a horizontal line that tells you to play that note short .  Dynamic markings can tell you how loud you should play a note or section . String instruments will use bowing marks, which look like a downward caret or a small table . Composers will use other dynamics, such as pianississimo (ppp) or fortississim (fff) to change the mood of the piece .  Some songs have an even more complex structure . To keep from rewriting the same music, you might use da capo (D. C. ) or dal segno . Da capo means to go back to the beginning of the piece . The Ancient Greeks wrote notation on stone as early as the first century .  Early music took a lot of time to write because copyists had to use a quill and ink . Composers would still write music by hand, but they would give their manuscript to a copyist . This helped save time when writing music for large groups . In the Baroque era (1600-1750), many composers used figured bass .  The invention and advancement of computers gave way to music notation software . Some composers have started using extended techniques for various instruments that are hard or impossible to notate with standard staves . Notating parts with electronics is another advancement in music .  Sheet music is an incredible tool that musicians can use for many things . Be sure to consider the elements of sheet music as well as its history . Then, you can enjoy reading new pieces of music and improving your skills .
